32. 8. insolentiam. The variety and contradictions in the opinions about the divine nature, a consequence of the ignorance which has incited men to philosophize and to form so various opinions on the subject, might serve as a weighty prool, maguum argumentum, sor the general proposition, that all philosophical investigation, that is, the striving after knowledge, has its foundation and starting point in ignorance. Arist. Met. 1, 2: διὰ τὸ φεύγειν τὴν ἄγνοιαν ἐφιλοσόφησαν.
